3) Create an abstract class Employee:
Properties:
name
id
Abstract method:
calculateSalary()

Create PermanentEmployee and ContractEmployee with different salary formulas.
-->abstract class Employee {

    String name;
    int id;

    Employee(String name, int id) {
        this.name = name;
        this.id = id;
    }

    abstract double calculateSalary();
}

class PermanentEmployee extends Employee {

    double salary;

    PermanentEmployee(String name, int id, double salary) {
        super(name, id);
        this.salary = salary;
    }

    double calculateSalary() {
        return salary + 5000;
    }
}

class ContractEmployee extends Employee {

    int hours;
    double rate;

    ContractEmployee(String name, int id, int hours, double rate) {
        super(name, id);
        this.hours = hours;
        this.rate = rate;
    }

    double calculateSalary() {
        return hours * rate;
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Employee e1 = new PermanentEmployee("Karthikeya", 101, 30000);
        Employee e2 = new ContractEmployee("Ravi", 102, 20, 500);

        System.out.println(e1.calculateSalary());
        System.out.println(e2.calculateSalary());
    }
}



4) Create an abstract class Order:
Properties:
orderId
customerName
Abstract method:
calculateBill()

Create subclasses OnlineOrder, CashOnDeliveryOrder with different bill logics.
-->
abstract class Order {

    int orderId;
    String customerName;

    Order(int orderId, String customerName) {
        this.orderId = orderId;
        this.customerName = customerName;
    }

    abstract double calculateBill();
}

class OnlineOrder extends Order {

    double amount;

    OnlineOrder(int orderId, String customerName, double amount) {
        super(orderId, customerName);
        this.amount = amount;
    }

    double calculateBill() {
        return amount + 50;
    }
}

class CashOnDeliveryOrder extends Order {

    double amount;

    CashOnDeliveryOrder(int orderId, String customerName, double amount) {
        super(orderId, customerName);
        this.amount = amount;
    }

    double calculateBill() {
        return amount + 100;
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Order o1 = new OnlineOrder(1, "Karthikeya", 1000);
        Order o2 = new CashOnDeliveryOrder(2, "Ravi", 1000);

        System.out.println(o1.calculateBill());
        System.out.println(o2.calculateBill());
    }
}





5) Try changing the access modifier of the abstract method:
public
private
protected
default
final abstract
static abstract

Write down which are allowed and which cause compile errors.
-->
| Modifier           | Allowed or Error | Reason                                                  |
| ------------------ | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------- |
| public abstract    | Allowed          | Accessible everywhere                                   |
| protected abstract | Allowed          | Accessible within package and subclass                  |
| default abstract   | Allowed          | Package-level access                                    |
| private abstract   | Compile Error    | Private methods cannot be overridden                    |
| final abstract     | Compile Error    | final prevents overriding, abstract requires overriding |
| static abstract    | Compile Error    | static methods belong to class and cannot be overridden |



6) Write a Java program to demonstrate how interfaces help achieve loose coupling.
-->interface Engine {

    void start();
}

class PetrolEngine implements Engine {

    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Petrol Engine Started");
    }
}

class DieselEngine implements Engine {

    public void start() {
        System.out.println("Diesel Engine Started");
    }
}

class Car {

    Engine e;

    Car(Engine e) {
        this.e = e;
    }

    void drive() {
        e.start();
        System.out.println("Car is Running");
    }
}

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Engine e1 = new PetrolEngine();
        Car c1 = new Car(e1);
        c1.drive();

        Engine e2 = new DieselEngine();
        Car c2 = new Car(e2);
        c2.drive();
    }
}
